anRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"107349","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/107349"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 55-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department with a four-day history of fever, sore throat, and malaise. He has treatment-resistant schizophrenia which has been well-controlled for the past eight years on clozapine. His other medical conditions include hypertension, type 2 diabetes mellitus, and rheumatoid arthritis, for which he takes perindopril, metformin, amlodipine, and methotrexate. He has been fully adherent with his medications and regular monitoring.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears unwell. His pulse rate is 110/min, blood pressure 125/85 mmHg, respiratory rate 22/min, SpO2 96% on room air, and temperature 38.5\u00b0C. There are several shallow ulcers in his mouth. Chest examination reveals scattered crackles throughout both lung fields. His most recent clozapine level three weeks ago was therapeutic at 450 ng/mL (350-600).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ELaboratory investigations reveal:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhite cell count: 1.8 x 10^9/L (4.0-11.0)\u003Cbr /\u003ENeutrophils: 0.2 x 10^9/L (2.0-7.5)\u003Cbr /\u003ELymphocytes: 1.2 x 10^9/L (1.0-4.0)\u003Cbr /\u003EPlatelets: 250 x 10^9/L (150-400)\u003Cbr /\u003EC-reactive protein: 85 mg/L (\u0026lt;5)\u003Cbr /\u003EMethotrexate level: 0.15 \u00b5mol/L (\u0026lt;0.23)\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely cause of his current presentation?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Methotrexate toxicity","Viral infection","Rheumatoid arthritis flare","Clozapine","Systemic lupus erythematosus"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis case presents a complex diagnostic challenge in a patient with multiple medical conditions and medications that could potentially cause bone marrow suppression. The key is to recognise the pattern and timing of presentation that points to clozapine as the culprit.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EClozapine\u003C/strong\u003E is the most likely cause of this presentation. The severe neutropenia (neutrophils 0.2 x 10^9/L) in conjunction with fever, sore throat, and oral ulcers is classic for clozapine-induced agranulocytosis. While most cases occur early in treatment, it can occur at any time. The presence of therapeutic clozapine levels does not exclude this diagnosis as it is an idiosyncratic rather than dose-dependent reaction.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMethotrexate toxicity\u003C/strong\u003E is a reasonable consideration given the patient\u0027s rheumatoid arthritis. However, the methotrexate level is within the therapeutic range, and methotrexate typically causes pancytopenia rather than isolated neutropenia.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Eviral infection\u003C/strong\u003E could explain the respiratory findings and fever, but would typically cause lymphopenia rather than severe neutropenia. The degree of neutropenia seen here is too severe to be explained by a viral infection alone.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Erheumatoid arthritis flare\u003C/strong\u003E would not typically cause such severe neutropenia. While rheumatoid arthritis can be associated with mild cytopenias, the acute presentation with fever and severe isolated neutropenia points to a different cause.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESystemic lupus erythematosus\u003C/strong\u003E can cause oral ulcers and cytopenias, but the acute presentation and severe isolated neutropenia would be unusual. Additionally, there are no other typical features such as rash, arthritis, or serositis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThis case emphasises the importance of considering clozapine-induced agranulocytosis even in the presence of other potential causes of neutropenia, and the need for urgent investigation of fever or flu-like symptoms in patients taking clozapine regardless of duration of treatment.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Clozapine-induced agranulocytosis can occur at any time during treatment, even after years of stable therapy.","Fever, sore throat, and flu-like symptoms in patients on clozapine require urgent investigation even if other causes seem more likely.","The presence of therapeutic drug levels does not exclude serious adverse effects of clozapine as many are idiosyncratic rather than dose-dependent."],"references":["Australian Medicines Handbook (online). Adelaide: Australian Medicines Handbook Pty Ltd; [2024] [April]. Available from: https://amhonline.amh.net.au/","Meyer N, Gee S, Whiskey E, Taylor D, Mijovic A, Gaughran F, Shergill S, MacCabe JH. Optimizing outcomes in clozapine rechallenge following neutropenia: a cohort analysis. The Journal of Clinical Psychiatry. 2015 Nov 25;76(11):13499. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/26646037/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"89834"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2072"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"89834","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/89834"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-06-28T15:05:49+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-07-08T09:09:07+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2072"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"107349"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"10","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/10"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udfad","name":"Psychiatry","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:46+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"13","links":{"self":"https://app